The high surface-to-volume ratio represented by the adoption of a cylindrical radial junction increases both the active depletion region as well as the overall surface area of the device, which then becomes more susceptible to recombination of photogenerated charge carriers. In addition, the band bending arising from Fermi-level pinning at the surface of NW must also be taken into account in the electrical simulation. In view of this, we assume acceptor-like surface trap states, whose energy level lies near the middle of the energy band gap, are located at the surface of n-type GaInP shell layer. According to the surface recombination model given by Stevenson and Keyes [15], the recombination rate can be described as:1RS,t=Ntrapσnσpvnthvpthnsps−ni,eff2σnvnthns+n1+σpvpthps+p1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
